metadata.name: Drifters #93
metadata.description:
In an undiscovered area, you've stumbled upon an unknown creature.
It looks weirdly haunting, and you're feeling a sense of unease.

You're wondering what it's doing.

It seems to move in patterns, and sometimes suddenly changes course.
Is it communicating?

(to whom?)

Setting aside your discomfort for a moment, you're realizing you could be seeing it wrong.
While the creature does look eerie and its motivations are unclear,
you realize every culture has its own appreciation of aesthetics,
and you can't help noticing there is a certain grace to this performance.

And it all makes sense.

You're witnessing uncharted explorations of elegance.

‚Äì

metadata.name: ecolog√≠as - A #544
metadata.description:
ecolog√≠as - A

lines are a metaphor for the communication all species engage in. We as humans have a need to leave traces - stories - that others can read and learn from. What will be the traces machines want to leave? This piece employs sinusoidal signals drawn with lines as a simple metaphor for every trace and every language, for every message and every communication.

ecolog√≠as-A is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecolog√≠as B and ecolog√≠as C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro
CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Reading a book #15
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: aether:Astral Loom #96
metadata.description:
Weaving on the astral plane. Lines of transmission. 
Some journeys are straightforward, others yield a multitude of pathways.
Disconnect to interpret.

(As an experiment) the rarity values assigned to this artwork are completely arbitrary, and are in no way connected to the visual output of the minted piece. One might wonder, why have rarity values at all? That's what I ask myself any time I see a value based on rarity attributes instead of viewer aesthetic. 

That being said, I suppose it's up to each person to decide for themselves the value of art...

This artwork was created using p5js.

linktr.ee/lisaorthstudio
twitter: @lisaorthstudio

metadata.name: Annum #5512
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: Vertical World #60
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.
